(27, 1, '2012-05-07 08:59:27', '2012-05-07 08:59:27', 'You certainly don''t go to Satay Kingdom for the decor or the service. A little hole in the wall off Cuba Street''s leftbank, amongst a cluster of other tiny restaurants - from Vietnamese to Mexican - it''s a nice spot to pick up some quality southeast asian fare.\n\nDespite the poky decor (hell, partly <em>because</em> of it) Satay Kingdom has been serving up very good Malaysian food for 10 years or so, despite being tucked away off the beaten track. This location, actually results in a huge plus - it''s one of the few Malaysian restaurants in Welly with an outdoor dining area. And let''s be honest, it''s slightly dingy interior and "what the hell are you doing here?" service kind of add to the overall experience too. Seriously, if you''re looking for fine dining while you''re eating Malaysian, then you''re doing it wrong.\n\nThey offer excellent - albiet typical - variations of the usual Malaysian favourites such as roti chanai, nasi goreng, mee goreng, and so on. But it''s a good idea (as it is with any restaurant of this type) to try some of the less-standard dishes: nyonya chicken, nasi kampong, kung po chicken and more. When the matron-like service lady angrily slaps it down on your table, you''ll be glad you did.\n\nI got the nyonya chicken which is a mix of stir fried chicken and veges fried in a soy-like sauce with rice on the side. Great stuff. Trish got the chicken roti chinai - arguably the house special - which was great, as it is at most malaysian places, and comes with a decent sized stack of excellent roti bread. We also got the chicken satay sticks (great, but pretty hard to mess up) and some fried Chinese style dumplings that were pretty good but lacked spice and were a bit over-crispy. Only thirty-five bucks for the whole lot plus a few cans of coke too. Great value.\n\nWhile arguably not the best Malaysian joint in town, it''s certainly up there, and any restaurant that can truck along steadily for over a decade on a minor thoroughfare is certainly doing something right. With the minimalist decor you can almost picture yourself swatting away sandflies whilst being yelled at by a tuk tuk driver as you wait for your food. A good thing, trust me.\n\n\n\n\n', 'Satay Kingdom', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '13-revision-8', '', '', '2012-05-07 08:59:27', '2012-05-07 08:59:27', '', 13, 'http://wellykai.co.nz/2012/05/13-revision-8/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
